data.title: Application of a hydrophobic microporous material in vehicle suspension
data.meta_description: Automotive suspension systems are important parts of vehicles and are vital for ride comfort, safety, and handling stability. Various active and semi-active sus
data.text:
As shown in Fig. 5, the suspension spring container has three main parts: (i) the molecular-spring chamber full of water and ZIF-8, (ii) the hydraulic-fluid chamber filled with oil, and (iii) the seal seat. A rubber diaphragm is used as an important sealing between the upper and lower chambers, and a linear bearing is used to reduce the friction on the bonding surface between the piston rod and the seal seat.

We define the piston–rod diameter as D, the compressibility of the liquid water as ηW, the compressibility of the aviation hydraulic fluid as ηO, the initial volume of the water as V1, the initial volume of the aviation hydraulic fluid as V2, the measured porous volume as Vpv, the intrusion pressure as Pi, the saturation pressure as Ps, the mass of the payload as M, and the mass of materials as m.

In the first stage, only these two liquids are compressed. Because an external pressure less than Pi cannot overcome the Laplace capillary pressure, the stiffness at this time can be estimated from the volume of compressed liquids. When the external pressure is higher than the saturation pressure Ps, the third stage begins to work. Because the nanopores are full of water, the reduced volume is still from water and oil in this process.

The amounts of compression of the two liquids are given as

ΔVW=Vw⋅ηW⋅(P−P0),

(5)

ΔVO=Vo⋅ηO⋅(P−P0),

(6)

where ∆VW and ∆VO are the amounts of compression of the water and oil, respectively, P is the external pressure, and P0 is the atmospheric pressure; however, P is much larger than P0, so the latter can be ignored.

Let the vertical displacement of the piston rod be x. Then, the process can be written as

ΔVW+ΔVO=x⋅14⋅π⋅D2,

(7)

i.e.,

P=x⋅14⋅π⋅D2/(Vw⋅ηW+Vo⋅ηO).

(8)

Then, the force–displacement relationship and the stiffness in the bearing stage can be written, respectively, as

F=x⋅14⋅π⋅D22/(Vw⋅ηW+Vo⋅ηO),

(9)

K1=14⋅π⋅D22/(Vw⋅ηW+Vo⋅ηO).

(10)

The principle of the stiffness model in the stopping stage is the same as that in the bearing stage, so the stopping-stage stiffness model is omitted. We assume linear stiffness for the working segment. Then, the suspension spring static stiffness model K0 in the working stage is written as

K0=FΔx=3.14×D2×(Ps−Pi)Vpv×m.

(11)

Figure 6 shows the test process of the suspension spring for quasi-static loading. The static characteristics of the suspension spring were tested using an electrohydraulic servo fatigue machine (HDT254A; WANCE, China). Apparently, according to Fig. 7, different from the control group for which only pure water was loaded into the suspension spring, the suspension spring with ZIF-8 exhibited obvious HSLD stiffness (high static and low dynamic stiffness). Actually, Fig. 7 clearly shows the agreement between the experimental and theoretical force–displacement curves, where the blue and red lines correspond to the experimental results and the black line corresponds to the theoretical prediction [Eqs. (10) and (11)]. The lines show the correctness of the theoretical model; the deviations in the bearing and stopping stages are due to residual air in the device, which was difficult to remove because the material was powdery.

According to Fig. 8, the suspension spring shows a hysteretic intrusion–extrusion cycle. The hysteresis loop remains constant after repeated tests. In addition, the hysteresis loop indicates that the mixture of water and ZIF-8 is better suited as a suspension spring than a shock absorber.

According to GB/T 15168-2013(a Chinese national standard), dynamic characteristics of the suspension spring are different from the result of quasi-static loading test because of the hysteresis.32 Hence, for a hysteresis system, the dynamic stiffness is a more realistic solution. According to this standard, first, the suspension spring is pressed to the static equilibrium position shown in Fig. 8. Second, hysteresis cycles with different amplitudes at fixed frequency are measured. Third, the slope of the diagonal line (expressed by BC) of the hysteretic intrusion–extrusion cycle shown in Fig. 9 is calculated. The slope is actually the dynamic stiffness at that amplitude. Finally, the dynamic stiffness curve (expressed by red circles) can be obtained. According to Fig. 9, the dynamic stiffness curve is close to the static test result (black line). Hence, for the convenience of the following analysis, the paper uses the latter, where hysteresis is ignored.

Figure 10 shows that a frequency of less than 12 Hz makes little difference to the hysteretic intrusion–extrusion cycle. This phenomenon indicates that the simplification of hysteresis in this paper is feasible.

According to Fig. 11, the suspension spring offers a considerable advantage over linear springs. The red and blue lines represent the stiffnesses of two different linear springs. For a given payload, the stiffness K0 of the suspension spring is lower than the corresponding linear-spring stiffness K1 under the same static displacement, and when K0 = K2, the static displacement of the corresponding linear spring is ∼1.5 times that of the suspension spring.

To make dynamic analysis easier, only 4 g of ZIF-8 was loaded into the suspension spring. To fit the experimental data, we used the cubic polynomial

f(x)=a3×x3+a2×x2+a1×x+a0,

(12)

where a3 = 2.869 × 107, a2 = 8.837 × 104, a1 = 5.983 × 104, and a0 = −0.000 483. However, given the relative smallness of a0, it is ignored in the subsequent analysis. The fitting results are shown in Fig. 13.

Figure 14 shows the vibration isolation system with one degree of freedom; when the load is in the static equilibrium position, the dynamic equation of the system is

Mẍ+cẋ+fx=F⁡cosωt,

(13)

where M and c are the load and damping coefficients, respectively, and f(x) is the nonlinear elastic restoring force. The test results indicate that a cubic polynomial fits the stiffness of the suspension spring during the working section when less than 5 g of ZIF-8 is loaded into the suspension spring. The nonlinear elastic restoring force is given as

fx=k0x+Fb1,(x>x1),a1x+a2x2+a3x3,(−x1≤x≤x1),k0x+Fb2,(x<−x1),

(14)

where a1, a2, and a3 are the stiffness coefficients of each order in the working stage, k0 is the stiffness of the other two stages, x1 and −x1 are the turning points of the different stiffnesses, and

Fb1=a1+a2x1+a3x12⋅x1−k0x1,

Fb2=−a1+a2x1+a3x12⋅x1+k0x1.

The averaging method used here involves a first-order approximation of the analytical solution of a nonlinear vibration system, based on which Eq. (13) is simplified as

ẍ+ω2x=ε−c0ẋ+F0⁡cosωt−gx,

(15)

where

gx=ω02−σx+fb1,(x>x1),−σx+r2x2+r3x3,(−x1<x<x1),ω02−σx+fb2,(x<−x1).

(16)

Here, we have ε=k0a1−1⁠, c0=cMε⁠, F0=FMε⁠, ω0=a1M⁠, ω2=ω02+εσ⁠, r2=a2Mε⁠, r3=a3Mε⁠, fb1=Fb1Mε⁠, and fb2=Fb2Mε⁠.

When ε = 0, Eq. (15) becomes

ẍ+ω2x=0,

(17)

the solution of which is

x=A⁡cosωt−θ,

(18)

and the derivative of x is

ẋ=−Aω⁡sinωt−θ,

(19)

where A is the amplitude. When ε ≠ 0, the solution of Eq. (17) is actually different from Eq. (13). However, ε and θ are viewed as being functions of time t as long as ε is small enough, so we introduce

φ=ωt−θ.

(20)

After differentiating with respect to t, Eq. (18) becomes

ẋ=Ȧcosφ−Aω⁡sinφ+Aθ̇sinφ.

(21)

Obviously, the left-hand side of Eq. (21) can be replaced by the right-hand side of Eq. (19) to give

Ȧcosφ+Aθ̇sinφ=0.

(22)

Equally, after differentiating with respect to t, Eq. (19) becomes

ẍ=−Ȧω⁡sinφ−Aω2⁡cosφ+Aθ̇ω⁡cosφ.

(23)

Based on the aforementioned equations, the differential equations for Ȧ and θ̇ are obtained as

Ȧ=−εω−c0ẋ+F0⁡cosωt−gxsinφ,

(24)

θ̇=εωa−c0ẋ+F0⁡cosωt−gxcosφ.

(25)

Because A and θ are slowly varying functions, the right-hand sides of Eqs. (24) and (25) can be approximated by the average of φ over a period, whereupon their averaged equation is

Ȧ=−εω⋅12π∫02π−c0⋅−Aω⁡sin⁡φ+F0⁡cosωt−gAcosφ×sin⁡φdφ=−ε2ωΦA,ω−F0⁡sinθ,

(26)

θ̇=εωA⋅12π∫02π−c0⋅−Aω⁡sin⁡φ+F0⁡cosωt−gA⁡cos⁡φ×cos⁡φdφ=ε2ωAΨA,ω+F0⁡cosθ,

(27)

where

ΦA,ω=1π∫02π−−c0Aω⁡sin⁡φ+gA⁡cos⁡φsin⁡φdφ,ΨA,ω=1π∫02π−−c0Aω⁡sin⁡φ+gA⁡cos⁡φcos⁡φdφ.

(28)

Combining Eqs. (26) and (27) gives

dAdθ=−aΦA,ω−F0⁡sin⁡θΨA,ω+F0⁡cos⁡θ.

(29)

Having set the excitation parameters, the singular point in the A−θ phase plane given by Eq. (29) is the steady-state response of Eq. (15) and is evaluated by

ΦA,ω−F0⁡sin⁡θ=0,

(30)

ΨA,ω+F0⁡cos⁡θ=0.

(31)

By eliminating the variable θ, the amplitude–frequency and phase–frequency equations are given as

Φ2+Ψ2+F02=0,

(32)

tanθ=−ΦΨ,

(33)

and the expressions for Φ and Ψ are obtained via integral transforms of Eq. (28).

In the nonlinear steady-state response of this suspension spring, there may be unexcited frequencies such as subharmonic and superharmonic ones, so the force transmissibility FT of the suspension spring is defined as the ratio of the root-mean-square (rms) values of the transmitted force and the excitation force, i.e.,

FT=20×lgRMS(gt(t))RMS(F0(t)),

(34)

where F0(t) is the excitation force and gt(t) is the transmitted force. Then, the index for evaluating the vibration isolation performance is obtained by taking the logarithm of the force transmissibility, i.e.,

TF=20lgFT.

(35)

From Fig. 15, it can be seen that when 4 g of ZIF-8 is loaded into the suspension spring, the natural frequency of the vibration isolation system is as low as 2.5 Hz compared to that of the control group (4.3 Hz) for which only pure water is loaded into the suspension spring. The value of FT is an important reference for evaluating the performance of a vibration isolator: if FT does not exceed 0 dB, then the vibration isolator helps decrease the energy transferred from the external input to the base; if FT ≤ −20 dB, then the vibration isolator performs excellently after a certain frequency. For the suspension spring with ZIF-8, as well as its lower natural frequency, it satisfies the second criterion mentioned above, i.e., the power transferred to the load is reduced by more than 90% when the excitation frequency exceeds 7.1 Hz.

In the field of multi-domain simulation and model-based design, benefiting from its block diagram environment, MATLAB Simulink has been a good choice. In this software, a block implements a certain function on its inputs and returns the corresponding results, and blocks are selected and linked based on equations of motion.33

The frequency of the front suspension of a passenger vehicle is usually less than 1.5 Hz. To satisfy that requirement, 8 g of ZIF-8 was loaded into the suspension spring to achieve lower stiffness. From the stiffness curve obtained from the experiment, the fitted curve was obtained easily using MATLAB. To meet the required fitting accuracy, a sixth-degree polynomial [Eq. (36)] was needed in Fig. 16, i.e.,

f(x)=p1↔x6+p2↔x5+p3↔x4+p4↔x3+p5↔x2+p6↔x+p7,

(36)

where p1 = 1.3334 × 109, p2 = 2.434 × 108, p3 = −1.883 × 106, p4 = 5.185 × 106, p5 = 0.000 486 3, p6 = 0.021 06, and p7 = 2.347. The fitted curve was then used in the Simulink quarter-vehicle model.

Before the simulation, we had to establish the equations of motion of the quarter-vehicle model with the suspension spring, which is a system with two degrees of freedom involving the two masses Mu (the unsprung mass) and Ms (the sprung mass, i.e., the car body). The automobile suspension is represented by the suspension spring and a damper in parallel. All the cases of the suspension system considered herein are shown in Fig. 17. The equations of motion are

Msẍs+cẋs−ẋu+KPSxs−xu=0,

(37)

Muẍu+cẋu−ẋs+KPSxu−xs+Kt(xu−xr)=0,

(38)

where xr is the road excitation as given by filtered white noise, x, ẋ, and ẍ are the displacement, velocity, and acceleration, respectively, Kt is the stiffness of the tire, and KPS and c are the variable stiffness and damping coefficient of the automobile suspension, respectively.

Equations (36)–(38) were used to establish a MATLAB Simulink model for the quarter-vehicle model, as shown in Fig. 18. A simulation was performed to plot the vehicle performance regarding body acceleration, its power spectral density (PSD), and suspension deflection. Figure 19 shows the peak value of the vehicle’s body acceleration, which generally must not exceed 1 g, and the peak value of the body acceleration with this suspension is far less than that.

Figure 20 contains two peaks: one (1.3 Hz) is the natural frequency of the sprung mass, and the other (12.1 Hz) is the natural frequency of the unsprung mass. As is known, the frequency of the front suspension of a passenger vehicle is usually less than 1.5 Hz, and Fig. 20 shows that this suspension can achieve that requirement. If the suspension spring is replaced by a linear spring (i.e., a traditional passive suspension), then its stiffness must be as low as 20 000 N/m to have the same resonant frequency. However, the suspension deflection with the linear spring (i.e., a traditional passive suspension) is greater than that with this suspension, as shown in Fig. 21. A well-known and thorny problem when designing an automotive suspension is dealing with the conflicting demands of ride comfort, low suspension working space, and good handling properties. Because the natural frequencies of both the proposed and traditional suspension can be adjusted, the PSD of the body acceleration with the traditional suspension is not shown in Fig. 20.

The weighted rms acceleration (aw) of the sprung mass is used to evaluate the ride comfort, where aw is expressed as34

aw=∫0.540W2(f)Ga(f)df12,

(39)

where

W(f)=0.5(0<f<2Hz),f/4(2<f<4Hz),1(4<f<12.5Hz),12.5/f(12.5<f<40Hz).

Table II shows the relationship between aw and the comfort reaction to the vibration environment.

TABLE II.

aw (m/s2) . Human response . <0.315 Not uncomfortable 0.315–0.63 A little uncomfortable 0.5–1 Fairly uncomfortable 0.8–1.6 Uncomfortable 1.25–2.5 Very uncomfortable >2 Extremely uncomfortable

aw (m/s2) . Human response . <0.315 Not uncomfortable 0.315–0.63 A little uncomfortable 0.5–1 Fairly uncomfortable 0.8–1.6 Uncomfortable 1.25–2.5 Very uncomfortable >2 Extremely uncomfortable

Figure 22 shows the relationship between weighted rms acceleration, speed, and road class, where A–D represent different road classes according to the ISO 2631-1 road classification. Even if the speed reaches 90 km/h, the weighted rms acceleration is still less than 0.315 m/s2 (in road classes A and B). For road class D, when the speed is low, the human response is a little uncomfortable. In summary, this suspension offers another choice when designing the configuration of a vehicle suspension.
